:"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","nickname for a person with dark or fair hair, from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ (Old English <i>blæc</i>) or ‘fair’ (Old English <i>blāc</i>) + <i>hed</i>, <i>heved</i> ‘head’. See also   Black  .","nickname from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ + <i>hod</i> ‘hood’."],"variants":[{"name":"Black","meanings":["English and Scottish: chiefly from Middle English <i>blak(e)</i> ‘black’ (Old English <i>blæc</i>, <i>blaca</i>), a nickname given from the earliest times to a swarthy or dark-haired man. However, Middle English <i>blac</i> also meant ‘pale, wan’, a reflex of Old English <i>blāc</i> ‘pale, white’ with a shortened vowel. Compare   Blatch   and   Blick  . With rare exceptions it is impossible to disambiguate these antithetical senses in Middle English surnames. The same difficulty arises with   Blake   and   Block  .","Scottish: in Gaelic-speaking areas this name was adopted as a translation of the epithet <i>dubh</i> ‘dark, black-(haired)’, or of various other names based on Gaelic <i>dubh</i> ‘black’, see   Duff  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames directly or indirectly derived from the adjective meaning ‘black, dark’, for example German and Jewish   Schwarz   and Slavic surnames beginning with <i>Čern-</i>, <i>Chern-</i> (see   Chern   and   Cherne  ), <i>Chorn-</i>, <i>Crn-</i> or <i>Czern-</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":3,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":28,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused